of Daniel Boone.

00:24:52.360 --> 00:24:57.180
But more to the point, Flanders
Calloway was Boone's son-in-law,

00:24:57.180 --> 00:25:01.810
and if Rebecca Boone died in
the cabin of Flanders Calloway,

00:25:01.810 --> 00:25:05.420
and another piece of information
made it clear that Boone lived

00:25:05.420 --> 00:25:10.170
for part of his last
six years, 1814 to 1820,

00:25:10.170 --> 00:25:15.460
in Flanders Calloway's house,
well then William Wells Brown grew

00:25:15.460 --> 00:25:18.130
up next door to Daniel Boone.

00:25:18.130 --> 00:25:26.570
I looked hard for physical evidence
of what that area looked like.

00:25:26.570 --> 00:25:29.960
Of course the most wonderful,

00:25:29.960 --> 00:25:35.440
but nonexistent photograph would've
been a likeness of the young cabin,

00:25:35.440 --> 00:25:38.710
but this is Flanders
Calloway's homestead.

00:25:38.710 --> 00:25:40.930
No date. I don't know
when it was taken.

00:25:40.930 --> 00:25:45.100
Looks to me to be 19th century,
but this would be very close.

00:25:45.100 --> 00:25:49.470
Young's house would've been
much larger, and much fancier.

00:25:51.250 --> 00:25:57.290
A year later Ricky and I after
a year or eight or nine months

00:25:57.290 --> 00:26:00.190
in Wooster, on our
drive back to Dallas.

00:26:00.190 --> 00:26:02.840
We're now in the summer of 2010,

