00:26:55.670 --> 00:26:58.940
and by this point how does
one write a book like this.

00:26:58.940 --> 00:27:03.840
One relies on a lot of professional
friends, librarians, archivists,

00:27:03.840 --> 00:27:09.500
scholars, and we by appointment
met up with the director

00:27:09.500 --> 00:27:11.500
of the local historical society.

00:27:11.500 --> 00:27:14.630
That's Kathy Sharpinwars,
as well as the head

00:27:14.630 --> 00:27:19.340
of the Missouri State archives
from St. Louis, Mike Everman,

00:27:19.340 --> 00:27:23.150
and his wife Diane, a
professional archaeologist.

00:27:23.150 --> 00:27:29.550
And by the time we met up
with them in July of 2010,

00:27:29.550 --> 00:27:34.420
we realized that we were
standing the whole time.

00:27:34.420 --> 00:27:40.850 position:56%
The moment we got out of her car the
year before, all the land around.

00:27:40.850 --> 00:27:44.940
The place of the restoration, the
municipal park, the parking lot,

00:27:44.940 --> 00:27:49.700
the cornfields all around, and the
town of Martinsville on the top

00:27:49.700 --> 00:27:54.290
of the hill that all of this was
the original John Young estate.,

00:27:54.290 --> 00:27:57.870
Which is to say, the moment we got
out of our car, we were walking

00:27:57.870 --> 00:28:03.350 position:56%
on the same land on which William
Wells Brown had spent his childhood.

00:28:03.350 --> 00:28:07.020
So we came back we hoped
to see what we could see

00:28:07.020 --> 00:28:10.230
through the eyes of professionals.

00:28:10.230 --> 00:28:14.320
And so, Ricky's taking
the photographs.

00:28:14.320 --> 00:28:17.600
Here we are walking the grounds,

00:28:17.600 --> 00:28:21.800
and it probably hasn't
changed all that much.

00:28:21.800 --> 00:28:23.390
The lower lying land.

00:28:23.390 --> 00:28:28.550
This is very fertile land is
very close to the Missouri River,

00:28:28.550 --> 00:28:31.230
midsummer, lots of corn growing.

00:28:31.230 --> 00:28:36.060
So we walked the land
looking for marks

00:28:36.060 --> 00:28:41.500
like survey marks of
the original plot.

00:28:41.500 --> 00:28:49.670
Here we are further along, and
I'm afraid not much really to see.

00:28:49.670 --> 00:28:51.320
A restoration.

00:28:51.320 --> 00:28:54.310
This is actually in the
center of Martinsville.

00:28:54.310 --> 00:28:57.340
We did find some of
the original spots

00:28:57.340 --> 00:29:00.420
where Young owned property
in Marthasville.

00:29:00.420 --> 00:29:03.540
We don't know where
the original house was.

00:29:03.540 --> 00:29:08.330
You know, I suppose that somebody
with supersonic technology,

00:29:08.330 --> 00:29:13.290
you know, maybe Henry Louis
Gates could get an aircraft fly

00:29:13.290 --> 00:29:18.680 position:56%
over this area, you know, with
sensory devices, and find, you know,

00:29:18.680 --> 00:29:23.440
where the bones, you know,
of the historical past were.

00:29:23.440 --> 00:29:27.250 position:56%
We did this, you know, the hard way.

00:29:27.250 --> 00:29:31.060
And just to update the historical
narrative, because we are talking

00:29:31.060 --> 00:29:35.740
about one of the pioneers
of African-American history.

00:29:35.740 --> 00:29:38.030
Four years later I think, thanks

00:29:38.030 --> 00:29:42.770
to Kathy Sharpinwars
they've put up a new sign.

00:29:42.770 --> 00:29:44.890
This went up in the
last four months.

00:29:44.890 --> 00:29:46.750
Sorry, it's not a very
good photograph.

00:29:46.750 --> 00:29:50.300
But finally, in the year
of his bicentennial,

00:29:50.300 --> 00:29:54.780
William Wells Brown has
entered the official narrative

00:29:54.780 --> 00:29:58.990
of Marthasville and
Missouri history.

00:30:00.040 --> 00:30:03.980
I'm going to skip over a segment.

00:30:03.980 --> 00:30:09.470
Sorry, we just don't
have enough time.

00:30:09.470 --> 00:30:15.080
I want to talk a little
bit about archives.

00:30:15.080 --> 00:30:18.200
That was our first archive,
in a manner speaking.

00:30:18.200 --> 00:30:21.650
The remains of a physical location

00:30:21.650 --> 00:30:25.950
and the narrative that
got attached to it.

00:30:25.950 --> 00:30:30.320
William Wells Brown spent
five years in England,

00:30:30.320 --> 00:30:35.560
technically is a fugitive
slave from 1849 to 1854.

00:30:35.560 --> 00:30:37.730
While in England he brought

00:30:37.730 --> 00:30:40.940
out an Anglo-Irish
edition of his narrative.

00:30:40.940 --> 00:30:44.150
He brought out a new
edition of his songbook.

00:30:44.150 --> 00:30:50.550
He wrote the first African-American
travelogue three years in England.

00:30:50.550 --> 00:30:52.570
And he brought out --
he wrote and brought

00:30:52.570 --> 00:30:54.980
out the first African-American
novel.

00:30:54.980 --> 00:30:56.610
He was a busy man.

00:30:56.610 --> 00:30:58.470
All of that he did on the side.

00:30:58.470 --> 00:31:02.120
He was the best known
African-American lecturer

00:31:02.120 --> 00:31:05.150
in the British Isles in the 1850's.

00:31:05.150 --> 00:31:08.210
He was a phenomenon.

00:31:09.310 --> 00:31:13.910 position:56%
The reason he went in the beginning,
besides his sheer interest

00:31:13.910 --> 00:31:20.040
in spreading his wings, was
that even though a noncitizen,

00:31:20.040 --> 00:31:23.190
technically a nonperson
in the United States.

00:31:23.190 --> 00:31:24.930
He was an official delegate

00:31:24.930 --> 00:31:32.120
to the third international peace
Congress meeting in Paris, France.

00:31:32.120 --> 00:31:37.910
And while there, he was one of the
most electrifying speakers there.

00:31:37.910 --> 00:31:41.370
He made some very important
contacts.

00:31:41.370 --> 00:31:46.010
One was with an English
aristocrat by the name of John Lee.

00:31:46.010 --> 00:31:48.820 position:56%
The strangest kind of an aristocrat.

00:31:48.820 --> 00:31:51.560
An aristocrat who leaned left.

00:31:51.560 --> 00:31:56.240
And Lee, who was by way a
cousin of the Lee's of Virginia,

00:31:56.240 --> 00:32:02.520 position:56%
including Robert E Lee, took a quick
interest in Brown and invited him

00:32:02.520 --> 00:32:07.740 position:56%
when they got back to England, as
well as some of the other delegates,

00:32:07.740 --> 00:32:14.980
to come visit at his country estate
about an hour north of London.

00:32:16.390 --> 00:32:23.640 position:56%
And here you have a measure of a
live person born in the slave shanty

00:32:23.640 --> 00:32:29.080
in the bluegrass country of
Kentucky, an honored guest at one

00:32:29.080 --> 00:32:32.510
of the finest mansions
in all of England.

00:32:32.510 --> 00:32:39.550
This, by the way, was the site
of Louis XVIII court in exile

00:32:39.550 --> 00:32:41.410
in the early 19th century.

00:32:41.410 --> 00:32:45.470
It's an absolutely
magnificent house.

00:32:45.470 --> 00:32:48.160
The back view.

00:32:48.160 --> 00:32:52.210
What makes it most interesting
and really the reason that Ricky

00:32:52.210 --> 00:32:57.000
and I went up there was Brown
mentions in his travelogue

00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:03.870
that Lee had his name inscribed on
a brick, and the brick installed --

00:33:03.870 --> 00:33:07.930
Lee was one of the leading amateur
astronomers in the British Isles.

00:33:07.930 --> 00:33:12.030
In the vault of Lees Observatory.

00:33:12.030 --> 00:33:14.840
It was the firmament
of great people.

00:33:14.840 --> 00:33:19.020
I don't know who the other
folks were, and we were hoping

00:33:19.020 --> 00:33:21.520 position:56%
that we would actually get a chance.

00:33:21.520 --> 00:33:23.930
We had to figure out how
to get into this house.

00:33:23.930 --> 00:33:25.600
But once we had done that,

00:33:25.600 --> 00:33:30.590
get a chance to see this
remarkable testament

00:33:30.590 --> 00:33:33.000
to the young William Wells Brown.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:38.370
Well, it turns out, everything we
looked for physically in England,

00:33:38.370 --> 00:33:42.740
from Brown's period, just about
everything, no longer existed.

00:33:42.740 --> 00:33:46.940
This great house suffered a
major fire in the early 1960's.

00:33:46.940 --> 00:33:49.170
They restored it, but
they had no reason

00:33:49.170 --> 00:33:52.870
to restore the observatory,
so that part was gone.

00:33:52.870 --> 00:33:57.930
We figured though it would have
been the corner that abut outward

00:33:57.930 --> 00:34:02.360
on this side, on the left side.

00:34:04.630 --> 00:34:10.360
Now, very quickly I want to
circle back to the United States,

00:34:10.360 --> 00:34:14.910
and to Brown's view of Washington.

00:34:14.910 --> 00:34:20.140
And as I said, it's not
an entirely happy view

00:34:20.140 --> 00:34:24.000
of our nation's capital
in the 1850's.

00:34:38.040 --> 00:34:41.330
While in England, Brown
had Washington on his mind.

00:34:41.330 --> 00:34:43.380
He read the American newspapers.

00:34:43.380 --> 00:34:46.420
He knew what was going on
with the Fugitive Slave Bill.

00:34:46.420 --> 00:34:50.290
It basically meant he was staying
in England for a good long time.

00:34:50.290 --> 00:34:53.950
He couldn't come back,
too well-known.

00:34:53.950 --> 00:34:59.760
And so he dug in and did
quite a lot of writing.

00:34:59.760 --> 00:35:03.660
Two particular works by Brown
that relates to the portrayal

00:35:03.660 --> 00:35:07.170
of Washington, and they're both
very interesting and very powerful.

00:35:07.170 --> 00:35:10.980
Brown produced the first
African-American panorama

00:35:10.980 --> 00:35:14.270 position:56%
that was shown in the British Isles.

00:35:14.270 --> 00:35:19.530
The panorama was an enormous
narrative painting done

00:35:19.530 --> 00:35:26.210
on heavy canvas, rolled up on
scrolls, and presented in a way

00:35:26.210 --> 00:35:28.860
that might remind one
of moving pictures.

00:35:28.860 --> 00:35:33.780
It was a form of visual technology
that basically was the precedent

00:35:33.780 --> 00:35:38.070
to the predecessor
to moving pictures.

00:35:38.070 --> 00:35:43.720
Brown apparently commissioned
250 yards of canvas

00:35:43.720 --> 00:35:47.750
in 24 views, and he would perform.

00:35:47.750 --> 00:35:51.820
He would show it at night
in a dimly lit room.

00:35:51.820 --> 00:35:53.330
He would often sing.

00:35:53.330 --> 00:35:56.980
He was a wonderful singer,
and he would tell the story.

00:35:56.980 --> 00:36:00.800
One of the 24 views was
his view of Washington.

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:06.070
And basically what Brown was doing
was rewriting American narrative

00:36:06.070 --> 00:36:08.980
history from an African-American
point of view,

00:36:08.980 --> 00:36:15.230
as well as the visuals that went
with it turning them into a kind

00:36:15.230 --> 00:36:20.920
of visual art that was
suitable for the presentation

00:36:20.920 --> 00:36:23.380
of African-Americans and
African-American history.

00:36:23.380 --> 00:36:27.820 position:56%
This was enormously ambitious tasks.

00:36:27.820 --> 00:36:31.030
Virtually none of the old
panoramas have survived.

00:36:31.030 --> 00:36:33.400
But Brown's had a catalog,

00:36:33.400 --> 00:36:36.940
so we know from the
catalog what the panorama,

00:36:36.940 --> 00:36:39.960
what the 24 views looked like.

00:36:39.960 --> 00:36:42.700
One of them is very reminiscent.

00:36:42.700 --> 00:36:47.390
For those of you who have seen 12
Years a Slave, you may remember

00:36:47.390 --> 00:36:52.530
that the director made a point
when Northrop is being held

00:36:52.530 --> 00:36:58.740
in a Washington prison of
cutting out and showing the tops

00:36:58.740 --> 00:37:04.390
of buildings with the top
of the capital sticking

00:37:04.390 --> 00:37:09.080
up to give the viewer a
sense of the proximity,

00:37:09.080 --> 00:37:12.860
in a manner speaking
of slavery and freedom.

00:37:12.860 --> 00:37:18.750
The problem of American democracy,
and that was one of Brown's scenes.

00:37:18.750 --> 00:37:20.880
Brown's is even richer.

00:37:20.880 --> 00:37:25.740
Brown's takes place in 1848
when there's a mass celebration

00:37:25.740 --> 00:37:29.550
in Washington of the
revolutions for freedom

00:37:29.550 --> 00:37:31.990
that had broken out across Europe.

00:37:31.990 --> 00:37:35.670
And in the backdrop,
are the slave pens.

00:37:35.670 --> 00:37:40.880
And for Brown this was the correct
way of presenting American history,

00:37:40.880 --> 00:37:43.410 position:56%
and especially our nation's capital.

00:37:43.410 --> 00:37:46.400
At that point, Brown had
never been to Washington.

00:37:46.400 --> 00:37:49.780
He would come actually
only after the Civil War.

00:37:49.780 --> 00:37:51.110
He was a generalization

00:37:51.110 --> 00:37:55.780
of the Freedman's Monument
to Abraham Lincoln.

00:37:55.780 --> 00:38:02.500 position:56%
The other work, visual work that
Brown produced, this may be familiar

00:38:02.500 --> 00:38:08.280 position:56%
to least a few of you is the famous
illustration from his novel, Clotel.

00:38:08.280 --> 00:38:14.070
Clotel, the story, fictitious,
but not entirely an accurate story

00:38:14.070 --> 00:38:17.250
of the slave daughter
of Thomas Jefferson

00:38:17.250 --> 00:38:21.470
and Jefferson's slave girl Sally.

00:38:21.470 --> 00:38:28.400
At the end of the story Clotel
returns to rescue her daughter held

00:38:28.400 --> 00:38:33.220
in Virginia, is recaptured, sent
off to Washington to be held

00:38:33.220 --> 00:38:36.690
in a slave pen until she
can be transported back

00:38:36.690 --> 00:38:39.120
to her master in Mississippi.

00:38:39.120 --> 00:38:44.290
Escapes the slave pens, runs
across Washington and is running

00:38:44.290 --> 00:38:49.090
across the long bridge from
Washington to Alexandria.

00:38:49.090 --> 00:38:53.690
She's cut off on both
ends, and in desperation,

00:38:53.690 --> 00:38:58.770
as this illustration
shows jumps to her death.

00:38:58.770 --> 00:39:02.680
For William Wells Brown,
historian of America

00:39:02.680 --> 00:39:06.030 position:56%
and the African-American experience,

00:39:06.030 --> 00:39:11.090
Washington DC was the
nub of the problem.

00:39:11.090 --> 00:39:13.290
And from his perspective.

00:39:13.290 --> 00:39:15.660
Remember, he's still
in London unable

00:39:15.660 --> 00:39:18.030
to get back to the United States.

00:39:18.030 --> 00:39:23.510
This was the situation in the
United States through the 1850s,

00:39:23.510 --> 00:39:26.810
and perhaps I should close
on a more hopeful note.

00:39:26.810 --> 00:39:31.900
As I mentioned, after the Civil
War, Brown would come to Washington

00:39:31.900 --> 00:39:38.050
for the first time and he was,
I think it was in 1867 he came

00:39:38.050 --> 00:39:41.130
to Washington, Maryland
and Virginia.

00:39:41.130 --> 00:39:42.920
He met officials.

00:39:42.920 --> 00:39:44.800
He took in the city.

00:39:44.800 --> 00:39:47.110
He met the African-American
community,

00:39:47.110 --> 00:39:51.040
and he went out into the country to
meet the real people, his people.

00:39:51.040 --> 00:39:56.280
The people he'd grown up with,
for the most part in Missouri.

00:39:56.280 --> 00:40:00.060
And he came away enormously
optimistic.

00:40:00.060 --> 00:40:04.000
And as generalizations of
the Freedman's Memorial

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:11.370
to Lincoln thought this was the
proper way that we can pay respect

00:40:11.370 --> 00:40:13.370
to the great emancipator.

00:40:13.370 --> 00:40:17.970
That actually was a project that
had a very complicated history,

00:40:17.970 --> 00:40:22.010
but Brown eventually came
around to seeing Washington.

00:40:22.010 --> 00:40:23.590
You know, as we say today,

00:40:23.590 --> 00:40:27.640
is Washington the problem
or the solution?

00:40:27.640 --> 00:40:32.710
William Wells Brown
would say yes, and yes.

00:40:32.710 --> 00:40:34.510
Thank you for your attention.

00:40:34.510 --> 00:40:44.540
[ Applause ]

00:40:44.540 --> 00:40:55.140
&gt;&gt; I have a few questions Ezra.

00:40:56.350 --> 00:40:57.840
Yes.

00:40:57.840 --> 00:41:12.010
&gt;&gt; So how did you -- I've never

00:41:14.100 --> 00:41:19.760
until today I never heard
of William Wells Brown.

00:41:19.760 --> 00:41:26.590 position:56%
So did you discover him and what led
you to, you know, take on this task,

00:41:26.590 --> 00:41:30.410
you know, uncovering
his life and trying

00:41:30.410 --> 00:41:36.950
to put together this little bits
of information of, you know,

00:41:36.950 --> 00:41:39.500
of putting his story together.

00:41:39.500 --> 00:41:41.710
Thank you so much for doing so.

00:41:41.710 --> 00:41:44.540
&gt;&gt; This is a question
I've been asked many times

00:41:44.540 --> 00:41:47.110
as I was working on the project.

00:41:47.110 --> 00:41:49.930
Why write a biography of Brown?

00:41:49.930 --> 00:41:57.190
And, you know, I think the way
you're posing the question leads

00:41:57.190 --> 00:41:59.300
to part of the answer.

00:41:59.300 --> 00:42:07.150
That this was a story, a life
story that needed to be written.

00:42:07.150 --> 00:42:10.080 position:56%
This was an absolutely amazing life.

00:42:10.080 --> 00:42:14.490 position:56%
You know, in one sense Brown was
the most inventive cultural creative

00:42:14.490 --> 00:42:17.670
figure in the United
States in the 19th century.

00:42:17.670 --> 00:42:19.540
And I'm a lover of Whitman.

00:42:19.540 --> 00:42:22.840
I put in a lot of time on
Whitman, but Brown did more things

00:42:22.840 --> 00:42:24.980
in more ways, and that's
part of the answer also.

00:42:24.980 --> 00:42:26.280
I knew of Brown as
the author of Clotel.

00:42:26.280 --> 00:42:29.800
American Lit scholars have known
about Clotel for a long time.

00:42:29.800 --> 00:42:33.570
When I read his play, his
historic play, The Escape,

00:42:33.570 --> 00:42:36.470
I was absolutely stunned.

00:42:36.470 --> 00:42:40.210
It was to my mind, to
my sense immediately one

00:42:40.210 --> 00:42:44.350
of the best American
place of the 19th century.

00:42:44.350 --> 00:42:47.120
And almost totally unknown,
and almost totally unstaged,

00:42:47.120 --> 00:42:51.750
except when in his own life
Brown took it on the road

00:42:51.750 --> 00:42:55.290
and did one-man recitations
of all the roles.

00:42:55.290 --> 00:42:58.750
All the white roles, all the black
roles, so I thought, you know,

00:42:58.750 --> 00:43:00.870
all these works by one
person, a narrative of a life.

00:43:00.870 --> 00:43:04.030
One of the most amazing lives of
the 19th century, and, you know,

00:43:04.030 --> 00:43:05.650
you always have to ask yourself
is this something that I can do.

00:43:05.650 --> 00:43:06.950
You know, does it fit my skill set?

00:43:06.950 --> 00:43:08.290 position:56%
And then I guess the final
ingredient was his sensibility spoke

00:43:08.290 --> 00:43:09.590
to my sensibility.

00:43:09.590 --> 00:43:10.890
You know, in a basic
way, I get Brown.

00:43:10.890 --> 00:43:12.690
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:43:12.690 --> 00:43:16.050
[ Inaudible ]

00:43:16.050 --> 00:43:18.430
&gt;&gt; Was he self educated?

00:43:18.430 --> 00:43:20.870
&gt;&gt; Right. No formal education.

00:43:20.870 --> 00:43:25.030
We think he was functionally
illiterate

00:43:25.030 --> 00:43:27.700
when he escaped at the age of 19.

00:43:27.700 --> 00:43:34.050
You know, and so by our standards
when our kids are often colleged.

00:43:34.050 --> 00:43:37.040
Brown could not read or write.

00:43:37.040 --> 00:43:39.980
I'm going to be in
Lexington, Kentucky next week.

00:43:39.980 --> 00:43:42.890
Lexington believes that
Brown was born there,

00:43:42.890 --> 00:43:45.740
and that's unfortunately
