00:48:13.250 --> 00:48:15.380
that there were Brown associations.

00:48:15.380 --> 00:48:19.520
Also to research his
friends, and colleagues.

00:48:19.520 --> 00:48:23.640 position:56%
And I said earlier that I tried to
write Brown into the larger context.

00:48:23.640 --> 00:48:26.750
They're powerful reasons for
doing that, and one was that,

00:48:26.750 --> 00:48:28.340
that was Brown's basic premise.

00:48:28.340 --> 00:48:29.890
I mentioned Whitman.

00:48:29.890 --> 00:48:33.550
Whitman thought of himself
as utterly exceptional,

00:48:33.550 --> 00:48:38.220
and his exceptionalism
allowed him to turn himself

00:48:38.220 --> 00:48:41.390
into a representative figure.

00:48:41.390 --> 00:48:42.690
It's a paradox.

00:48:42.690 --> 00:48:44.580
Brown never thought of
himself as exceptional.

00:48:44.580 --> 00:48:47.660
He thought of himself
as an African-American,

00:48:47.660 --> 00:48:53.780
and so what he wrote, even how
he wrote was part in parcel

00:48:53.780 --> 00:48:55.690
of being one of the people.

00:48:55.690 --> 00:49:00.920
And therefore a way to get at
Brown was to go through the lives

00:49:00.920 --> 00:49:03.950
and sometimes the archives
of his fellows.

00:49:03.950 --> 00:49:07.160
The obvious figure is
Frederick Douglass, and Brown

00:49:07.160 --> 00:49:12.100
and Douglass are look-alikes
in many ways.

00:49:12.100 --> 00:49:14.430
You know, they're both
white father, black mother,

00:49:14.430 --> 00:49:16.330 position:56%
exceptional prodigious young people.

00:49:16.330 --> 00:49:20.010
Authors of two of the great
fugitive slave narratives,

00:49:20.010 --> 00:49:22.750
print-based figures, public
speakers, and, in fact,

00:49:22.750 --> 00:49:24.050
they often worked in concert.

00:49:24.050 --> 00:49:25.350
So I would work, if I couldn't go
into Brown through the front door,

00:49:25.350 --> 00:49:26.650
you know, I'd have to
find an alternative way.

00:49:26.650 --> 00:49:28.000
And a lot of that meant just going
archives wherever Brown lived.

00:49:36.040 --> 00:49:37.340 position:56%
&gt;&gt; How about the [inaudible] papers?

00:49:37.340 --> 00:49:41.870
I mean did you find much in
the way of correspondence?

00:49:41.870 --> 00:49:46.010
&gt;&gt; Well, we are the Library of
Congress, and the great archive

00:49:46.010 --> 00:49:50.050
in the field is the
Frederick Douglass papers.

00:49:50.050 --> 00:49:55.270
And their relationship, I found
