00:49:55.270 --> 00:49:56.890
It's actually a little
bit disappointing.

00:49:56.890 --> 00:49:58.530
There are no personal letters.

00:49:58.530 --> 00:50:00.430
And by the way, personal
letter from Brown

00:50:00.430 --> 00:50:03.040
to Douglass would be, how dare you.

00:50:03.040 --> 00:50:07.070
It would start with an
antagonistic statement.

00:50:07.070 --> 00:50:11.330
Douglass and Brown had a
very difficult relationship.

00:50:11.330 --> 00:50:14.270
In some ways it shouldn't
be surprising.

00:50:14.270 --> 00:50:18.170
These are big men, and when
big men or big people get

00:50:18.170 --> 00:50:22.030
into a room there's just not
enough oxygen to supply to,

00:50:22.030 --> 00:50:27.000
you know two major
breathing apparatuses.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:29.280
But there were professional
connections.

00:50:29.280 --> 00:50:35.150
Brown probably began his European
travelogue as a series of letters

00:50:35.150 --> 00:50:37.990
that were written to
first to the Northstar,

00:50:37.990 --> 00:50:39.660
Frederick Douglass's paper.

00:50:39.660 --> 00:50:40.960
And then when that switched

00:50:40.960 --> 00:50:45.480
over to the paper called Frederick
Douglass's Paper they were

00:50:45.480 --> 00:50:47.990
in a professional relationship.

00:50:47.990 --> 00:50:49.660
That was probably the first stage

00:50:49.660 --> 00:50:52.690
and then Brown probably
figured these are really good

00:50:52.690 --> 00:50:54.890
and I can turn it into a book.

00:50:54.890 --> 00:50:58.400
And there are documents
relating to that.

00:50:58.400 --> 00:51:01.580
And there are a couple
of scattered letters.

00:51:01.580 --> 00:51:08.420
One of the coincidences is that
the family that bought the freedom

00:51:08.420 --> 00:51:11.490
of Frederick Douglass,
a family from Newcastle

00:51:11.490 --> 00:51:14.600
in England was the same family

00:51:14.600 --> 00:51:17.790
that bought the freedom
of William Wells Brown.

00:51:17.790 --> 00:51:19.090
Their name was Richardson.

00:51:19.090 --> 00:51:23.330
These were remarkably fine people.

00:51:23.330 --> 00:51:27.370
Ellen Richardson is really
remarkable human being

00:51:27.370 --> 00:51:31.440
and both Douglass and Brown were
very close to Ellen Richardson,

00:51:31.440 --> 00:51:35.820
and Richardson's correspondence
with Douglass is here

00:51:35.820 --> 00:51:37.750
in the Library of Congress.

00:51:37.750 --> 00:51:44.870 position:56%
And when she wrote Douglass she
often associated Douglass with Brown

00:51:44.870 --> 00:51:48.770
and would ask, you know, what's
new with my old friend William

00:51:48.770 --> 00:51:52.040
who hasn't written me
in X number of years.

00:51:52.040 --> 00:51:57.870
So, you know, there are some very
small, but very cherished moments.

